"Pongratz J., Reick C.H., Raddatz T., Caldeira K., Claussen M.","Past land use decisions have increased mitigation potential of reforestation",2011,"Geophysical Research Letters","38","15", L15701,"","",,,10.1029/2011GL047848,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79961116951&partnerID=40&md5=82b8b0cec923867ddf8d8df9e02bafed","Department of Global Ecology, Carnegie Institution, 260 Panama St., Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Klima Campus, University of Hamburg, Hamburg, Germany","Pongratz, J., Department of Global Ecology, Carnegie Institution, 260 Panama St., Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Reick, C.H., Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Raddatz, T., Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Caldeira, K., Department of Global Ecology, Carnegie Institution, 260 Panama St., Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Claussen, M., Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany, Klima Campus, University of Hamburg, Hamburg, Germany","Anthropogenic land cover change (ALCC) influences global mean temperatures via counteracting effects: CO<inf>2</inf> emissions contribute to global warming, while biogeophysical effects, in particular the increase in surface albedo, often impose a cooling influence. Previous studies of idealized, large-scale deforestation found that albedo cooling dominates over CO <inf>2</inf> warming in boreal regions, indicating that boreal reforestation is not an effective mitigation tool. Here we show the importance of past land use decisions in influencing the mitigation potential of reforestation on these lands. In our simulations, CO<inf>2</inf> warming dominates over albedo cooling because past land use decisions resulted in the use of the most productive land with larger carbon stocks and less snow than on average. As a result past land use decisions extended CO<inf>2</inf> dominance to most agriculturally important regions in the world, suggesting that in most places reversion of past land cover change could contribute to climate change mitigation. While the relative magnitude of CO<inf>2</inf> and albedo effects remains uncertain, the historical land use pattern is found to be biased towards stronger CO<inf>2</inf> and weaker albedo effects as compared to idealized large-scale deforestation. Copyright 2011 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Deforestation; Global warming; Land use; Landforms; Reforestation; Revegetation; Solar radiation; Albedo effects; Boreal regions; Carbon stocks; Climate change mitigation; Global-mean temperature; Land use pattern; Land-cover change; Land-use decisions; Surface albedo; Carbon dioxide; albedo; carbon dioxide; carbon emission; climate change; cooling; deforestation; global warming; land cover; land use; nature-society relations; reforestation",,,,,,"Bala, G., Caldeira, K., Wickett, M., Phillips, T.J., Lobell, D.B., Delire, C., Mirin, A., Combined climate and carbon-cycle effects of large-scale deforestation (2007) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 104 (16), pp. 6550-6555. , DOI 10.1073/pnas.0608998104; Bathiany, S., Claussen, M., Brovkin, V., Raddatz, T., Gayler, V., Combined biogeophysical and biogeochemical effects of large-scale forest cover changes in the MPI Earth system model (2010) Biogeosciences, 7, pp. 1383-1399. , doi:10.5194/bg-7-1383-2010; Betts, R.A., Offset of the potential carbon sink from boreal fores-tation by decreases in surface albedo (2000) Nature, 408, pp. 187-190; Betts, R.A., Biogeophysical impacts of land use on present-day climate: Near-surface temperature change and radiative forcing (2001) Atmospheric Science Letters, 2 (1-4), pp. 1-13. , DOI 10.1006/asle.2001.0023, PII S1530261X01900234; Claussen, M., Brovkin, V., Ganopolski, A., Biophysical versus biogeochemical feedbacks of large-scale land co